### File Descriptions
```
- app.py
  The main backend Python application file implementing the entire web application logic using a web framework (e.g., Flask). It handles routing for all nine pages, reads and writes data to the local text files in the 'data' directory, processes user actions (search, filter, add to cart, checkout, write reviews, etc.), and renders HTML templates with dynamic data.

- data/
  Directory containing all the local text files used for data storage as specified:
  - books.txt: Stores book details.
  - categories.txt: Stores book categories.
  - cart.txt: Stores shopping cart items.
  - orders.txt: Stores order records.
  - order_items.txt: Stores individual items within orders.
  - reviews.txt: Stores customer reviews.
  - bestsellers.txt: Stores bestseller rankings.

- templates/
  Directory containing HTML template files for each page of the web application. Each template corresponds to one of the nine pages described in the requirements, structured with the specified element IDs for frontend interaction and dynamic content rendering:
  - dashboard.html: Dashboard page.
  - catalog.html: Book catalog with search and filter.
  - book_details.html: Detailed book information and reviews.
  - cart.html: Shopping cart management.
  - checkout.html: Checkout form.
  - order_history.html: Display past orders.
  - reviews.html: Customer reviews listing.
  - write_review.html: Form to submit new reviews.
  - bestsellers.html: Bestseller rankings.

- static/
  Directory for static assets used by the frontend:
  - css/styles.css: Stylesheet for consistent styling across pages.
  - js/scripts.js: JavaScript for client-side interactivity (e.g., button actions, dynamic filtering).
  - images/: Folder for storing book cover images and other graphical assets.

This structure keeps the backend logic consolidated in a single Python file for simplicity and maintainability, while separating frontend templates and static resources for clarity and modularity, fully meeting the project requirements.
